25. c. 06. in Sequanos. Caesar probably wished to maire Besanpon his headquarters. To get there from Gergovia he would ford the Loire at Bourbon Iancey, turn north so as to avoid the now hostile Aeduan country land at the same time to effect his junction with Labienus) as far as Joigny or thereabouts; then strike across by way of langres, cross the Saone at Gray or Pontaillier, and so arrive at Besancon. The battle now to be described was on the n'ver Vingeanne. See Jules Cesar (plate 24).

28. trinta caetris. Vercingetorix advanced from Bibracte by way of Thil Chatel and formed three camps on eminences, south of the Roman position, so as to command the three possible ways to Besancon, that by Gray, that by Pontailler‚ and that by Chalons sur Saone. He hoped in this way to be able to attack Caesar's army while still in colummae it neared the heights of Sacquenay on which he was posted.
